<BlogPost
	title="Boston to Old Orchard Beach by Car: The Complete Guide"
	description="About 95 miles up I-95. Tips on traffic, tolls, parking, and why Saco makes a better base than staying right in Old Orchard Beach."
	date="April 2026"
	category="Travel Guide"
	slug="boston-to-old-orchard-beach"
>
	<p>Old Orchard Beach is roughly 96 miles from Boston via I-95 — under two hours in good traffic. During a summer Friday afternoon? Budget three to four. Here's everything you need to know to make the drive go smoothly, including tolls, stops worth making, parking at the other end, and the case for basing yourself in Saco rather than Old Orchard Beach itself.</p>

	<h2>The Route</h2>

	<p>The drive is straightforward: <strong>Boston → I-93 North → I-95 North through New Hampshire → Maine Turnpike (I-95) → Exit 36, Saco</strong>. From Exit 36, you're about 5 minutes from Saco Bay Hotel and 10 minutes from the Old Orchard Beach pier.</p>

	<p>The Maine Turnpike begins at the New Hampshire border in Kittery. Saco and Old Orchard Beach are served by <strong>Maine Turnpike Exit 36</strong>.</p>

	<h2>Drive Times: The Honest Version</h2>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Normal conditions:</strong> 1 hour 37–48 minutes</li>
		<li><strong>Summer Friday afternoon:</strong> 2.5–4 hours (I-95 northbound through New Hampshire and into Maine is notoriously congested from roughly 2 PM through 8 PM)</li>
		<li><strong>Best departure windows on summer Fridays:</strong> Before noon, or after 7:30 PM</li>
		<li><strong>From Portland, ME:</strong> 20 minutes (19 miles)</li>
	</ul>

	<p>If you're coming on a summer weekend, leaving Boston before 10 AM or after 7:30 PM Friday significantly changes the experience. Midday Saturday and Sunday are manageable in both directions.</p>

	<h2>Tolls</h2>

	<p>Both New Hampshire and Maine charge tolls on I-95. Maine accepts <strong>both cash and E-ZPass</strong> at all plazas — no all-electronic pay-by-plate system, so you won't be surprised by a bill in the mail.</p>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Maine Turnpike (full length, Kittery to Augusta):</strong> $7.00 cash / ~$6.05–$6.70 with E-ZPass</li>
		<li><strong>New Hampshire Turnpike (I-95 through NH):</strong> Approximately $4.00 total northbound</li>
		<li><strong>Total tolls Boston to Saco (one way):</strong> Roughly $6–$10 depending on E-ZPass vs. cash</li>
	</ul>

	<p>A Maine-issued E-ZPass offers up to 40% off tolls for frequent travelers (40+ trips/month) — worth it if you're visiting multiple times per season.</p>

	<h2>Road Trip Stops Worth Making</h2>

	<h3>Portsmouth, NH (~56 miles from Boston)</h3>
	<p>Roughly 40 minutes outside Boston. Exit 7 from I-95 puts you in Market Square — cobblestone streets, local restaurants, craft breweries, and the Strawbery Banke Museum. A good breakfast or lunch stop if you're doing a morning departure. Portsmouth is a legitimately excellent small city that often gets driven past.</p>

	<h3>Kittery Outlets (~65 miles from Boston)</h3>
	<p>Right at the Maine border — I-95 Exit 3 or Exit 2. Over 120 name-brand outlet stores: Nike, Coach, lululemon, Eddie Bauer, Crate & Barrel, Kittery Trading Post. Savings of 25–65% every day. This is where you stop if the car has a teenager or anyone who needs new sandals before hitting the beach. Budget an hour.</p>

	<h3>Kennebunk/Kennebunkport (~81 miles from Boston)</h3>
	<p>I-95 Exit 25. Upscale, charming coastal village — great for a lunch stop before the final stretch to OOB. Dock Square has boutiques and good restaurants. Goose Rocks Beach and Kennebunk Beach are both nearby if you want a preview of the Maine coast before arriving in Saco.</p>

	<h2>Parking at Old Orchard Beach</h2>

	<p>Parking is the main logistical challenge for day visitors and anyone driving into OOB without a hotel in the town itself.</p>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Municipal lots and street parking:</strong> $3/hour (season runs roughly Memorial Day through Labor Day). Payable at kiosks or by app.</li>
		<li><strong>Private lots near the pier:</strong> $20–40 on peak summer weekends</li>
		<li><strong>Cheaper lots further from the pier:</strong> $5–10</li>
		<li><strong>Free residential street parking:</strong> Side streets north and south of downtown — often available with a 10–15 minute walk</li>
		<li><strong>Milliken Street area:</strong> A local tip — steps from the beach, typically less crowded than main lots</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Key rule:</strong> Arrive before 9 AM on summer weekends to secure parking before lots fill. On July 4th weekend, this is non-negotiable — convenient parking is gone by early afternoon.</p>

	<h2>The Amtrak Downeaster: The No-Parking Option</h2>

	<p>For visitors who'd rather not drive at all — or who are traveling without a car — the Amtrak Downeaster runs directly from Boston North Station to Old Orchard Beach station, which is <strong>within 100 yards of the beach</strong>.</p>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Travel time:</strong> Approximately 2 hours 11 minutes</li>
		<li><strong>Fares:</strong> Starting at $28–32 one way (Value Fares)</li>
		<li><strong>OOB station address:</strong> 11 First Street, Old Orchard Beach, ME 04064</li>
		<li><strong>Service:</strong> Seasonal (approximately May through mid-October); not all trains stop at OOB — check the timetable</li>
		<li><strong>Sample schedule:</strong> Train #681 departs Boston 8:50 AM, arrives OOB 11:25 AM</li>
		<li><strong>On board:</strong> Free Wi-Fi, café car</li>
		<li><strong>Booking:</strong> amtrakdowneaster.com or the Amtrak app</li>
	</ul>

	<p>The train eliminates parking costs and the stress of Friday traffic entirely. For a day trip to OOB from Boston, it's genuinely the better option.</p>

	<h2>Why Saco Makes a Better Base</h2>

	<p>Old Orchard Beach in summer is a resort town at full operational capacity — great for a day, intense for multiple nights. Saco, directly adjacent, offers a quieter residential feel with the same access. <strong>Maine Turnpike Exit 36 drops you directly into Saco</strong> — it's the natural first stop off the highway.</p>

	<p>From Saco Bay Hotel, the OOB pier is a 10-minute drive. Funtown Splashtown USA is 1.5 miles away. Ferry Beach State Park is 2 miles away. Downtown Biddeford — with some of the most acclaimed restaurants in Maine — is 10 minutes. You can spend your days at the beach and evenings somewhere significantly different.</p>

	<p>Staying in OOB puts you closer to the action but in the middle of resort-town traffic and summer pricing. Most guests who've done it both ways prefer the Saco base.</p>

	<div class="tip-box">
		<strong>Driving tip</strong>
		<p>If you're leaving Boston on a summer Friday, check the Maine Turnpike's real-time travel time data at maineturnpike.com before you leave. The difference between departing at 11 AM vs. 3 PM is often 45–90 minutes. If you can leave by noon, you'll arrive in Saco before the heavy traffic builds.</p>
	</div>
